</div></div><div class=3D"nist-callout"><p><strong>Dimensional analysis </s=
trong>is a technique used to convert measurements. For example, changing th=
e magnitude of a SI quantity or converting between SI and non-SI units. Som=
e measurements have one dimension, for example length. A square shape (area=
) has two dimensions (e.g., length and width), while a cube (volume) has th=
ree dimensions (e.g., length, width, and height). Converting between measur=
ement units is a very important skill when working within and between measu=
rement systems.</p><p>This problem-solving method is based on the principle=
 that quantities are defined as equalities. A <strong>conversion factor </s=
trong>is an expression for the relationship between units that is used to c=
hange the units of a measured quantity without changing the value. A <stron=
g>conversion ratio</strong> (or unit factor) always equals one (1), where t=
he numerator and the denominator have the same value expressed in different=
 units.</p></div><p>A <strong>numerator</strong> represents the parts out o=
f the whole or how much you have. A <strong>denominator</strong> represents=
 the total number of parts of the whole. In this example of the common frac=
tion =C2=BE, 3 is the numerator and 4 is the denominator. Performing the ma=
th calculation (3 divided by 4) transforms the number into a decimal fracti=
on, 0.75.</p>      <div class=3D"align-center nist-image">
     =20
    <img loading=3D"lazy" src=3D"https://www.nist.gov/sites/default/files/s=
tyles/220_x_220_limit/public/images/2021/04/29/Numerator%20Denominator.jpg?=
itok=3DJ_IwIoWs" width=3D"220" height=3D"68" alt=3D"Numerator 3 over Denomi=
nator 4" typeof=3D"foaf:Image">





                </div>
  <p>This method uses the fact that any number or expression can be multipl=
ied by "one" without changing its value. This allows the conversion of unit=
s by multiplying the initial measurement by one (or more) forms of the numb=
er 1. While the multiplication by 1 does not change the value of the measur=
ement, it does change the measurement units.</p>      <div class=3D"align-c=
enter nist-image">
     =20
    <img loading=3D"lazy" src=3D"https://www.nist.gov/sites/default/files/s=
tyles/480_x_480_limit/public/images/2021/04/29/Unit%20Conversion%202.png?it=
ok=3Dej5pcbEh" width=3D"461" height=3D"261" alt=3D"Unit Conversion Example"=
 typeof=3D"foaf:Image">





                </div>
  <h3 id=3D"unit-conversion-process"><strong>Unit Conversion Process</stron=
g><a class=3D"auto-anchor" title=3D"Permalink to this item" href=3D"https:/=
/www.nist.gov/pml/owm/metric-si/unit-conversion#unit-conversion-process"><i=
mg src=3D"https://www.nist.gov/libraries/nist-component-library/dist/img/li=
nk.svg" alt=3D"permalink"></a></h3><p>This process uses the fact that any n=
umber or expression can be multiplied by "one" without changing its value. =
This allows the conversion of units by multiplying the initial measurement =
by one (or more) forms of the number 1. While the multiplication by 1 does =
not change the value of the measurement, it does change the measurement uni=
ts.</p><p>It=E2=80=99s very easy to systematically apply unit conversion pr=
ocess to solve conversions within or between measurement systems. It may be=
 necessary to multiply by more than one conversion ratio in more complex co=
nversions. Use these steps to construct a unit conversion problem so one (o=
r more) of the units cancel until only the desired unit remains:</p><p><str=
ong>Step 1. </strong>Identify the unit you have. These are the <em>Starting=
 Units</em>.</p><p><strong>Step 2. </strong>Identify the unit you want. The=
se are the <em>Desired Units</em>.</p><p><strong>Step 3. </strong>Identify =
appropriate unit conversion factor(s). These are the <em>Linking (</em>or <=
em>Ratio) Unit(s)</em>. Use EXACT conversion factors whenever available.</p=
><p><strong>Step 4. </strong>Cancel units and perform the math calculations=
 (e.g., multiply, divide). Repeat the calculation (double check).</p><p><st=
rong>Step 5. </strong>Evaluate the result. Does the answer make sense?</p><=
h3 id=3D"best-practices"><strong>Best Practices</strong><a class=3D"auto-an=
chor" title=3D"Permalink to this item" href=3D"https://www.nist.gov/pml/owm=
/metric-si/unit-conversion#best-practices"><img src=3D"https://www.nist.gov=
/libraries/nist-component-library/dist/img/link.svg" alt=3D"permalink"></a>=
</h3><ul><li>Multiply the numerators (across) and denominators (across) to =
calculate an intermediate answer, then divide. Documenting the calculation =
steps can be especially helpful when problem-solving errors.</li><li>Do not=
 round any quantities used within the calculation.</li><li>Only round the f=
inal calculated quantity.</li></ul><p>Many unit conversion problems will re=
quire only a single unit conversion factor. However, multiple factors may b=
e required to solve a problem. These figures illustrate both examples. Reme=
mber that Step 3, <em>identifying the conversion factor</em>, is often the =
most challenging step. If an incorrect (or approximate) conversion factor i=
s used, a correct solution will not be achieved.</p>      <figure role=3D"g=
roup" class=3D" align-center nist-image">
<div>
     =20
    <img alt=3D"Unit Conversion" height=3D"297" loading=3D"lazy" src=3D"htt=
ps://www.nist.gov/sites/default/files/styles/480_x_480_limit/public/images/=
2021/04/29/Unit%20Conversion%203.png?itok=3DakPc5-rD" typeof=3D"foaf:Image"=
 width=3D"480">





                </div>
<figcaption class=3D"nist-image__caption">Credit: NIST</figcaption>
</figure>

  <p><strong>Example. </strong>An engineer has designed a new <strong>5 m</=
strong> computer cable but must represent the length in centimeters within =
an owner manual diagram. How many <strong>cm </strong>is the length?</p>   =
